.TH "gf" "1" "2024" "1.0.0"
.SH NAME
gf \- friendly file search tool with flexible filtering
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]gf\f[R] \-s \f[I]PATTERN\f[R] [\f[I]OPTIONS\f[R]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Welcome to \f[B]gf\f[R], a friendly and powerful file search tool
designed to make finding content in your files both easy and efficient.
Whether you\(cqre searching through code, logs, or any text files,
\f[B]gf\f[R] provides intuitive filtering options to help you find
exactly what you\(cqre looking for.
.PP
\f[B]gf\f[R] recursively searches for text patterns within files
starting from your current directory.
What makes it special is its flexible filtering system \- you can easily
target specific file types or ignore unwanted ones, making your searches
faster and more focused.
Perfect for developers, system administrators, and anyone who needs to
search through files regularly.
.SS Search Options
.TP
\f[B]\-s\f[R], \f[B]\(ensearch\f[R] \f[I]PATTERN\f[R]
The text pattern to search for within files (required).
Supports regular expressions for powerful pattern matching.
.SS File Filtering Options
.TP
\f[B]\-t\f[R], \f[B]\(entarget\f[R] \f[I]PATTERN\f[R]
Target specific file patterns to include in the search.
Use comma\-separated patterns like `\f[I].pl,\f[R].pm' to search only
Perl files, or `\f[I].js,\f[R].ts' for JavaScript/TypeScript files.
.TP
\f[B]\-i\f[R], \f[B]\(enignore\f[R] \f[I]PATTERN\f[R]
File patterns to exclude from the search.
Use comma\-separated patterns like `\f[I].log,\f[R].tmp' to ignore log
and temporary files, keeping your results clean and relevant.
.SS Output Control Options
.TP
\f[B]\-c\f[R], \f[B]\(encontext\f[R] \f[I]NUMBER\f[R]
Show NUMBER of lines before and after each match for better context.
Helpful when you need to understand the surrounding code or content.
.TP
\f[B]\-m\f[R], \f[B]\(enmaxline\f[R] \f[I]NUMBER\f[R]
Limit the number of lines read from each file.
Useful for speeding up searches in large files or when you only care
about content near the beginning of files.
.SS Utility Options
.TP
\f[B]\-d\f[R], \f[B]\(endebug\f[R]
Enable detailed debug output to see what files are being processed and
how patterns are being matched.
.TP
\f[B]\-h\f[R], \f[B]\(enhelp\f[R]
Display comprehensive help information with examples and usage guidance.
.TP
\f[B]\-V\f[R], \f[B]\(enversion\f[R]
Show version information and author details.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Basic Searches
.TP
\f[B]gf \-s `function'\f[R]
Find all occurrences of `function' in files within the current directory
and subdirectories.
.TP
\f[B]gf \-s `TODO|FIXME'\f[R]
Search for either `TODO' or `FIXME' comments using regular expression
alternation.
.TP
\f[B]gf \-s `myRegex[ab]+'\f[R]
Use advanced regex patterns to find complex text patterns.
.SS File Type Filtering
.TP
\f[B]gf \-s `error' \-t `\f[BI].pl,\f[B].pm'\f[R]
Search for `error' only in Perl files (.pl and .pm extensions).
.TP
\f[B]gf \-s `function' \-t `\f[BI].js,\f[B].ts'\f[R]
Find `function' declarations in JavaScript and TypeScript files only.
.TP
\f[B]gf \-s `config' \-i `\f[BI].log,\f[B].tmp'\f[R]
Search for `config' while ignoring log files and temporary files.
.TP
\f[B]gf \-s `import' \-i `.git/\f[BI],node_modules/\f[B]'\f[R]
Find `import' statements while excluding version control and dependency
directories.
.SS Context and Output Control
.TP
\f[B]gf \-s `sub main' \-c 3\f[R]
Find `sub main' and show 3 lines of context before and after each match
for better understanding.
.TP
**gf \-s `class' \-c 5 \-t \(cq*.py\(cq**
Search for Python class definitions with 5 lines of context around each
match.
.TP
\f[B]gf \-s `import' \-m 100\f[R]
Look for `import' statements but only read the first 100 lines of each
file (useful for large files).
.SS Advanced Combined Usage
.TP
\f[B]gf \-s `error' \-t `\f[BI].pl\(cq \-c 2 \-i \(cq\f[B].bak'\f[R]
Complex search: find `error' in Perl files, show 2 lines of context, but
ignore backup files.
.TP
**gf \-s \(cqTODO.*urgent\(cq \-t `\f[I].c,\f[R].h' \-c 1**
Find urgent TODO comments in C source and header files with minimal
context.
.TP
\f[B]gf \-s `password|secret|key' \-i `\f[BI].log,\f[B].cache' \-d\f[R]
Security audit: find sensitive terms while ignoring logs and cache
files, with debug output.
.SS Real\-World Use Cases
.TP
\f[B]gf \-s `deprecated' \-t `\f[BI].pl,\f[B].pm' \-c 2\f[R]
Find deprecated function usage in a Perl codebase with context to
understand impact.
.TP
**gf \-s \(cqSELECT.*FROM\(cq \-t `\f[I].sql,\f[R].pl' \-i `\f[I].bak,\f[R].old'**
Find SQL SELECT statements in database\-related files, ignoring backup
files.
.TP
**gf \-s `console.log|print|echo' \-t \(cq\f[I].js,\f[R].php,*.sh\(cq \-c 1**
Find debug output statements across multiple scripting languages.
.SH CONFIGURATION
\f[B]gf\f[R] supports configuration files to set default ignore and
target patterns, making it easy to customize behavior for your specific
workflow without typing the same options repeatedly.
.SS Configuration File Locations
Configuration files are checked in the following order:
.TP
\f[B]\(ti/.gfconf\f[R]
User\-specific configuration file in your home directory.
This is the recommended location for personal settings.
.TP
\f[B]/etc/gfconf\f[R]
System\-wide configuration file.
Settings here apply to all users on the system.
.SS Configuration Syntax
Configuration files use a simple line\-based format with three main
directives:
.TP
\f[B]ignore\f[R] \f[I]PATTERN\f[R]
Add a file pattern to ignore during searches.
Multiple ignore directives can be used.
.TP
\f[B]target\f[R] \f[I]PATTERN\f[R]
Add a file pattern to target during searches.
Multiple target directives can be used.
.TP
\f[B]source\f[R] \f[I]PATH\f[R]
Include another configuration file.
Useful for sharing common settings across multiple config files.
.SS Pattern Matching
.IP \(bu 2
Patterns support standard shell wildcards (* and ?)
.IP \(bu 2
Patterns are case\-insensitive by default
.IP \(bu 2
Use full paths or relative patterns as needed
.IP \(bu 2
Multiple patterns can be specified with multiple directive lines
.SS Comments and Formatting
.IP \(bu 2
Lines starting with # are treated as comments
.IP \(bu 2
Empty lines are ignored
.IP \(bu 2
Leading and trailing whitespace is automatically trimmed
.SS Configuration Examples
.SS Basic User Configuration (\(ti/.gfconf)
.IP
.EX
# Common development file ignores
ignore *.log
ignore *.tmp
ignore *.bak
ignore *.old

# Version control and build artifacts
ignore .git/*
ignore .svn/*
ignore node_modules/*
ignore target/*
ignore build/*

# Target common source files by default
target *.pl
target *.pm
target *.js
target *.py
target *.c
target *.h
.EE
.SS Project\-Specific Configuration
.IP
.EX
# Web development project settings
ignore *.min.js
ignore *.min.css
ignore dist/*
ignore coverage/*

target *.html
target *.css
target *.js
target *.php

# Include team\-wide settings
source /shared/config/gf\-team.conf
.EE
.SS Advanced Configuration with Source Directive
.IP
.EX
# Main config file
source \(ti/.gfconf\-base

# Project\-specific additions
ignore vendor/*
ignore cache/*
target *.twig
target *.yml
.EE
.SS How Configuration Interacts with Command Line
.IP \(bu 2
Configuration file patterns are loaded first
.IP \(bu 2
Command\-line options (\-t, \-i) are added to configuration patterns
.IP \(bu 2
Command\-line options do not override configuration; they supplement it
.IP \(bu 2
If both target patterns exist (config + command line), files must match
at least one pattern from either source
.IP \(bu 2
If ignore patterns exist, files matching any ignore pattern are excluded
.SS Troubleshooting Configuration
.TP
\f[B]Permission Issues\f[R]
If a configuration file exists but cannot be read, \f[B]gf\f[R] will
display a warning and continue without that configuration.
.TP
\f[B]Invalid Syntax\f[R]
Unknown configuration directives will generate warnings but won\(cqt
stop execution.
.TP
\f[B]Missing Source Files\f[R]
If a source directive references a non\-existent file, a warning is
displayed and that directive is skipped.
.TP
\f[B]Debug Configuration\f[R]
Use the \-d (\(endebug) flag to see which configuration files are being
loaded and what patterns are being applied.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
\f[B]0\f[R]
Successful completion.
The search completed without errors, regardless of whether matches were
found.
.TP
\f[B]1\f[R]
Error occurred.
This includes invalid command line arguments, file permission issues,
missing search patterns, or other runtime errors.
.SH FILES
.TP
\f[B]\(ti/.gfconf\f[R]
User\-specific configuration file.
This is the primary location for personal gf settings and is checked
first.
.TP
\f[B]/etc/gfconf\f[R]
System\-wide configuration file.
Settings here apply to all users and are checked if no user\-specific
config exists.
.TP
\f[B]Additional configuration files\f[R]
Any files referenced by `source' directives in the main configuration
files.
.SH SEE ALSO
\f[B]grep\f[R](1), \f[B]find\f[R](1), \f[B]ag\f[R](1), \f[B]rg\f[R](1),
\f[B]ack\f[R](1)
.PP
\f[B]grep\f[R](1) \- The classic Unix text search utility.
\f[B]gf\f[R] provides more user\-friendly output and better file
filtering options.
.PP
\f[B]find\f[R](1) \- File system search utility.
Use with \f[B]gf\f[R] to pre\-filter directories before searching
content.
.PP
\f[B]ag\f[R](1) \- The Silver Searcher, a fast code search tool.
\f[B]gf\f[R] offers more flexible configuration options.
.PP
\f[B]rg\f[R](1) \- ripgrep, an extremely fast search tool.
\f[B]gf\f[R] provides a more approachable interface for casual users.
.PP
\f[B]ack\f[R](1) \- A grep\-like tool optimized for programmers.
\f[B]gf\f[R] offers similar functionality with simpler configuration.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
\f[B]HOME\f[R]
Used to locate the user\-specific configuration file at \(ti/.gfconf.
